results.notes:
I am growing Wine Cap mushrooms in wood chips in our front yard, with great success. One problem I have had is that when the weather is dry, the mushrooms don’t develop their characteristic burgundy red color; instead, they remain beige to light brown, particularly when they are mature.
I have now read repeatedly that Death Caps (Amanita Phalloides) have been sighted in Seattle, and am wondering whether there could be a risk that these sneak into our Wine Cap wood chip bed? The color of the cap could be similar to mature Wine Caps, and immature Wine Caps tend to have fairly light-colored gills (see photos). If I don’t check whether there is a vulva at the base of the stem, I am wondering whether i may accidentally harvest a Death Cap.
So, my questions:
1.) Could Death Caps theoretically cohabitate in our wood chips with Wine Caps?
2.) And am I correct that the mushrooms in the attached photos are young Wine Caps, not Death Caps?
Thank you!

results.notes:
Habitat: Saprobic on the deadwood of hardwoods or confers; growing in dense clusters, or scattered; widely distributed and common (Mushrooms of the Midwest)
Location: Muir Woods, Latitude 43.078 N, Longitude, 89.4039 W.
Identification Process: I used the identifying characteristics in the descriptions in Mushrooms of the Midwest book to identify this species. Even though someone had voted for Lycoperdon Perlatum, there were a few characteristics that fit more with Morganella Pyriformis. First, Morganella Pyriformis has a measurement range starting at 1.5 cm, but Lycoperdon has a measurement starting at 2.5 cm. From the photo, one can see that my species is closer to 1.5 cm. Second, Lycoperdon is shaped like an inverted pear, whereas my species is more or less round, which more accurately fits the description for Morganella Pyriformis. Finally, Morganella pyriformis is seasonally from spring through fall, whereas Lycooperdon marginatum is seasonally summer and fall. I saw mine during early spring. These three factors led me to believe my species is Morganella Pyrifrormis rather than Lycoperdon marginatum.
Substrate: hardwood

results.notes:
Two very young specimens fruiting in moss from the base of a big leaf maple(Acer macrophyllum). Undisturbed/natural-deep woodland habitat.
Cap: conical, distinctly flattened pits, light tan interior of pits.
Base of cap/stem connection tightly grooved/hooked narrowly.
Early season occurrence.4/29/22.
Stem: slightly granulose, cylindrical with slightly swollen base(small ribs/folds). Apex of cap(where it meets cap) folded into narrow groove(fold).
Harvested both specimens, bisected vertically and dehydrated for herbarium collection.
I have encountered this species at this location multiple times over the years(always in mid to late April).
Species this collection certainly is not(reasoning)-
Morchella eohespera: fruits late in season with Spruce. My collection was attached to base of Acer macrophyllum(hardwood) and fruits early Spring.
Pits are flattened.
Morchella norvegiensis: Also fruits late in season with Spruce.
Morchella tridentina: also occurs late, usually in mountains(not always). Morphology wrong.
Morchella prava/Morchella americana: pits are distinctly irregular with dark interior. Completely off for this collection.
Mel-8: not to be considered due to habitat/location.
All other Morchella that occur here in the PNW can be crossed of easily based on habitat/morphology.

Some areas of brown reaction in the one layer, best seen in the last photo at 100×. I think the reacting cells are the same type as the inflated cells seen photos labeled #A7-A9, except after dehydrating/rehydrating they are somewhat compressed and not as distinct as when found in the mount of fresh material. All photos of micro at 400x except for last photo labeled #A14 (100x).

results.notes:

Last two photos show the results. There appears to be two layers of cells (photo labeled B9, 400x). The layer of smallish polygonal cells appearing like a mosaic did not exhibit much of a reaction. Likely the same species as seen in obs 490834.

Habitat: Saprobic, growing in overlapping clusters on hardwood logs and stumps; causing a straw-colored sapwood rot in standing trees; widely distributed (Mushrooms of the Midwest).
Location: Muir Woods, Latitude 43.078 N, Longitude, 89.4039 W.
Identification Process: This one was a toss-up between Trametes villosa and Trichaptum biforme, and I went with Trichaptum biforme because of the defining characteristic that Trichaptum biforme is seasonally late spring and Trametes villosa was seasonally summer and fall. We were nowhere near summer at the time of the this collection. Furthermore, the dark coloring of the margin could be seen as pale lilac, which is another characteristic. Also, when I did the KOH test it came back negative, which was a chemical reaction factor that fit with Trichaptum birforme. Unfortunately, Trametes Villosa did not mention a chemcial test. Finally, in comparing the pictures of the underside of the species, it more closely visually represents Trichaptum biforme, rather than the pores to be nearly tooth-like or irregular, as described with Trametes Villosa.

Identification Process: I used the key from the book “Myxomycetes: A Handbook of Slime Molds” on page. 78 to select the species within the order Trichiales
1. I observed a fruiting body with a stalked sporangium. I then went to number 2. I then chose a sporangia with a well-developed stalk because I turned the sporangium to the side in the dissecting microscope and saw that the stalk was substantial. I then went to number 6 and chose the one that said Sporangia yellow to yellowish brown because it was not red, maroon, or red-brown. Number 8 in the key, I chose peridiucm persisting as fairly conspicuous because the “wall of the goblet” was obvious and persistent. Because it was Sporangia typically scattered to getregarious; stalk well-developed; peridium persisting as a relatively shallow but conspicuous calyculus determined that it was a Hemitrichia calyculata. I checked the picture in the book and it showed the picture which matched my slide. It looked the same as the capillitium. It also had the branching which is shown in one of my. pictures. The spores are a bit spikey just like my pictures.
